   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28586_1782_10_07_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworth's Town</placeName>
                  <lb/>
                  <date when="1782-10-07">October the 7<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. 1782.</date>
                  <lb/>
               </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p> You tell me my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HoarF1">Miss Robinson</persName> that you have been<lb/>
               obliged to drop all your correspondancies, I thank you for<lb/>
               reserving mine to be dropt <hi rend="underline">last</hi>. I own I feel some degree of self-<lb/>
               complacency at having foreseen that it must end so. You will<lb/>
               allow me to say, now you are convinced of it yourself, that I<lb/>
               thought it a little imprudent in you to correspond with so<lb/>
               many Young Ladies; if you recollect I declined writing to any<lb/>
               one except yourself and in so doing I was considered by some<lb/>
               proud, by others reserved and by all singular. I was <unclear>actuated</unclear>
               <lb/>
               by different motives; the young ladies who were so obliging to request of<lb/>
               me to write to them would I doubt not have been very glad to hear from<lb/>
               me for a month or two, but when once a correspondace is begun, I<lb/>
               think it must be more agreeable to both the parties to carry it<lb/>
               on. Time becomes more valuable as we grow older and it<lb/>
               requires a greater proportion of it to carry on a constant <choice>
                  <orig>corres-<lb/>
                  -pondance</orig>
                  <reg>correspondance</reg>
               </choice>, than I should wish to bestow on a mere <choice>
                  <orig>Acquain-<lb/>
                     -tance</orig>
                  <reg>acquaintance</reg>
               </choice>; I should think one must feel no small degree of<lb/>
               friendship for any one before one can always find something<lb/>
               to say to them, and what a task it is to be obliged to write to<lb/>
               <unclear>one</unclear>when when one has nothing to say, I hope my Dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HoarF1">Fanny</persName>
               <lb/>
               this will never be the case with us, but if it ever should<lb/>
               I shall be sincere enough to tell you so, and let me request<lb/>
               the same sincerity from you, for surely it will be better for<lb/>
               both of us to stop, before we have compleatly tired each other<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28586_1782_10_07_page02.jpg"/>
               
               I hope what I have said will not lead you to suspect<lb/>
               that I am already tired of your correspondence for I assure<lb/>
               you I mean it should have a quite contrary Effect, I mean to<lb/>
               convince you that it is entirely through inclination I write to<lb/>
               you.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GoldX1">A Brother</persName> of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GoldO1">Doctor Goldsmith</persName>'s was here a few days<lb/>
               ago. I daresay you have read and admired <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GoldO1">The D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
               </persName>'s <unclear/>
               <lb/>
               Works; we always are desirous to see any friend or relation<lb/>
               of an ingenious man, if Abilities could be left like Elisha's<lb/>
               Mantle to a successor their prejudice would be justifiable<lb/>
               But Alas! I fear the Heir or relation of a celebrated man<lb/>
               <del/>
               <lb/>
               seldom resembles him in any thing but a name or some<lb/>
               external peculiarity; but I think another and a more <choice>
                  <orig>rea-<lb/>
                  -sonable</orig>
                  <reg>reasonable</reg>
               </choice> cause may be assigned for this desire, a wish to <choice>
                  <orig>disco-<lb/>
                     -ver</orig>
                  <reg>discover</reg>
               </choice> the private character of one whose writings have given<lb/>
               us pleasure, or whom we have admired in a public capacity<lb/>
               <unclear>which</unclear> may be more readily discovered from little anecdotes<lb/>
               in his domestic life, than can be expected <add>from</add> the faint portrait<lb/>
               Historians have given us of him - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GoldX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. G.</persName> is a Cabinet Maker<lb/>
               and is esteemed ingenious in <hi rend="underline">his line of life</hi>. I fancy he is in<lb/>
               easy circumstances, but still one cannot help feeling a kind<lb/>
               of regret that a Brother of so <choice>
                  <orig>ingenious ingenious</orig>
                  <reg>ingenious</reg>
               </choice> a Man should<lb/>
               pass through life neglected and unknown we expect that<lb/>
               one who was so nearly connected with <del/>
               <add>him</add> who has <choice>
                  <orig>render-<lb/>
                  -ed</orig>
                  <reg>rendered</reg>
               </choice> himself deserving of fame and whom we have been <choice>
                  <orig>accus-<lb/>
               -tomed</orig>
                  <reg>accustomed</reg>
               </choice> to respect should share in that respect &amp; partake in<lb/>
               the fame he has acquired. -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#VanhX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>.. Vanhock</persName> and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#VanX1">Miss Van</persName> often used to speak<lb/>
               in high terms of a <persName ref="./Personography.xml#IrwiX2">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.. Irwin</persName> &amp; of his account of his Travels<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#IrwiX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>.. Irwin</persName> is our nearest Neighbour, she has a very pretty<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#IrwiX3">Sister</persName> - she <del>is</del> seems generally liked by all the Neighbourhood<lb/>
               I have not seen enough of her to form any opinion of her<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28586_1782_10_07_page03.jpg"/>
                  
               myself, and even if I had, I should be very cautious of giving<lb/>
               it, in <hi rend="underline">writing</hi> until I was fearfully convinced it was a <hi rend="underline">just</hi>
               <lb/>
               one - A false fact may be asserted, a hasty character may be<lb/>
               given in <hi rend="underline">conversa</hi>tion and may be pardoned or at least<lb/>
               is soon forgotten, but a person's <hi rend="underline">writing</hi> always remains on<lb/>
               record and may be produced at any time against them<lb/>
                  You will then do me the justice my d.<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HoarF1">Miss Robinson</persName>
               <del/>
               <lb/>
               whenever you think I am too reserved in my letters to you<lb/>
               to attribute it to motives of prudence - and not to any want<lb/>
               of friendship, or want of confidence in you. Reserve may<lb/>
               prevent a friendship <add>being</add> formed suddenly, but I am inclined<lb/>
               to believe that I those friendships last longest which <del/>
               <lb/>
               <add>are</add> longest in forming and those friends are generally most<lb/>
               worth <del/> obtaining whose regard it requires most<lb/>
               pains to gain.<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#InxxX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <unclear>In<gap/>
                  </unclear>
               </persName> abroad at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Mumbai_IN">Bombay</placeName> where it is probable he will <gap/>
               <lb/>
               my Brother - There are two <del/> fine drawings at <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BroxX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Bro<gap/>
               </persName>
               <lb/>
               his Mother in law's, drawn by his directions.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>I had a letter to day from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#PourX1">Miss Pourys</persName> she said <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SmytX1">Miss Smyth</persName>
               <lb/>
               had drank tea with her lately, they were well, I am sure they<lb/>
               are very happy in having so good a friend.<lb/>
               My eyes are not yet <hi rend="underline">well</hi> but I shall have a tooth drawn next<unclear/>
               <lb/>
               Week, pour un dernier resort, which I hope will be of more service<lb/>
               to me than any anything I have hitherto tried.<lb/>
               I must reproach you with having neglected to answer two questions<lb/>
               I asked you in my last, but I fancy I must reproach myself<lb/>
               for having written so long a letter.<lb/>
               If you like political subjects I have a great deal to say to you<lb/>
               on them but I will by no means force you to hear me.<lb/>
               Do not fail to remember me kindly to all, or <hi rend="underline">any</hi> of my<lb/>
               friends in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Wimpole_ENK">Wimpole S<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>.</placeName> you may chance to meet. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#AmicX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <unclear>Amici</unclear>
               </persName>
               <lb/>
               gone over to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IT">Italy</placeName>! well he will be happier there than in<lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName>, for with all his discernment &amp; good sense he<lb/>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM28586_1782_10_07_page04.jpg"/>
               
               appeared rather too strongly tinctured with partiality<lb/>
               for the manners &amp; customs of his Countrymen<lb/>
               "As which of us is not?"<lb/>
               I wish you would speak particularly kindly for me<lb/>
                  to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DeviE1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Devis</persName> &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoriX1">Miss Morison</persName> and pray tell me if you have<lb/>
                  heard any thing of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DeviE1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. D</persName>'s health. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#PowyX1">Miss Powys</persName> says it has<lb/>
               been but indifferent for some time past.<lb/>
               I do not know whether I who am myself too much inclined<lb/>
               to take no exercise can be allowed to observe that, <hi rend="underline">that</hi>
               <lb/>
                  may be one cause of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DeviE1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Devis</persName>'s want of Health joined to<lb/>
               her application and the anxiety she feels for the improvement<lb/>
                  and health of the Young Ladies under her care.<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               I am my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HoarF1">Miss Robinson</persName>, very sincerely your Friend<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
               <address>
                  <addrLine>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HoarF1">Miss Robinson</persName>
                  </addrLine>
                  <addrLine>
                     <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Cranford_ENK">Cranford</placeName>
                  </addrLine>
                  <addrLine>
                     <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Kettering_ENK">Kettering</placeName>
                  </addrLine>
                  <addrLine>
                     <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">England</placeName>.</addrLine>
               </address>
            </closer>
         </div>
